NEWCASTLE - Five suspects, accused of human trafficking, will be back in court next month.They are linked to a Newcastle clothing factory, where about seventy people have been forced to work against their will. The suspects, aged between 18 and 25, face charges including human trafficking, money laundering and contravening the Immigrations Act.They allegedly lured workers from Swaziland and Lesotho, forcing them to work 15-hour days for minimal pay.READ: Human trafficking suspects in courtThe factory's been shut down following a Hawks raid this month.The accused have all been denied bail.They are expected to appear in court again on the 29th of March. eNCA